        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "* Glucose 5% may be used in patients with sodium restriction."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 11
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Slow infusion is essential with loading dose so as to avoid Red Man Syndrome, hypotension or thrombophlebitis."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 12
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 2.3,
                "text": "Where fluid restriction is required with a peripheral line, a dilution of 10mg/ml with a longer infusion rate can be used i.e. 500mg in 50ml over 100mins & 1000mg in 100ml over 200mins."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 13
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 2.4,
                "text": "However, the risk of infusion-related undesirable effects can be increased with these higher concentrations. It is advisable to discuss with the ward pharmacist first."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 14
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.0,
                "text": "Maintenance Dose"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 15
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.1,
                "text": "Continuous intravenous infusion should follow straight after the loading dose and should be based on the patient's renal function, using creatinine clearance estimation."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 16
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.2,
                "text": "Table 2: Estimation of creatinine clearance"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 17
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "The following \u2018Cockcroft Gault' equation can be used to estimate creatinine clearance (CrCl)"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 18
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "CrCl = [140 \u2013 age (years)] x weight (kg) x F (mL/min) serum creatinine (micromol/L)"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 19
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "F=1.23 for males & 1.04 for females"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 20
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "Use actual body weight or Ideal body weight whichever is lower."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 21
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "See Appendix 1 below for ideal body weight table"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 22
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "In patients with low creatinine (< 60 micromol/L), use 60 micromol/L."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 23
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Note: Use of estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) is not recommended"
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 24
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.3,
                "text": "For central line administration, reconstitute each vancomycin 500mg vial with 10mls water for injection. Then make up the reconstituted vancomycin to 50mls sodium chloride 0.9% in a syringe pump."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 25
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.4,
                "text": "Each 50ml vancomycin infusion should be administered using an infusion pump; start a new syringe driver immediately after the previous one, and do not use a syringe driver beyond 24hours without changing."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 26
        },
        {
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.5,
                "text": "Refer to Table 3 for the Initial maintenance dose regimen. Follow-up dosing should be based on vancomycin serum concentration; see Table 5 for advice."
            },
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 27
        },
